So, after reading through this logic, the control flow still isn’t clear
to me. Why is `requestAnimationFrame` only called once, outside of
`step`, while `step` itself recurs synchronously? The `nEpochs`
variable, which appears to hold the target (maximum) number of epochs,
is initialized to `1`, but later mutated from within a _different_
asynchronous callback to the result of `initializeFit`, so which value
is used when?

Is there some way that we can restructure this to make the control flow
obvious from the structure of the code? For instance, if the initial
value of `1` for `nEpochs` is supposed to be an unobservable state, then
could we write something like

```typescript
async projectUmap(/* … */) {
  const nearest = await /* compute knnComputation */;
  const nEpochs = await util.runAsyncTask('Initializing UMAP…', () => {
    // …
    return this.umap.initializeFit(/* … */);
  });
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    const step = () => {
      // …
      requestAnimationFrame(step);
      // …
      if (done) resolve();
    };
    requestAnimationFrame(step);
  });
}
```

(I think that I’ve reached my short-term saturation on understanding
this function and allotting time to it, so I’ll come back to see what
you come up with. :-) )

